Title : Elizabeth Ewen
Text : '''Elizabeth Ewen''' was a scholar of [[women's history]], [[immigration]], and [[film]]. She was among the first [[feminist]] historians to write about early [[American cinema]].<ref name="McReynolds2003">{{cite book|author=Louise McReynolds|title=Russia at Play: Leisure Activities at the End of the Tsarist Era|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mHHl-iBCqKkC&pg=PA265|year=2003|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-4027-0|pages=265–}}</ref> Ewen was a professor of [[American Studies]] at the [[State University of New York at Old Westbury]] ([[SUNY]]).<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/04/books/review/Berreby.t.html " No ____ Need Apply"]. ''New York Times''. By DAVID BERREBY, February 4, 2007</ref>

Noted [[film historian]] [[Robert Sklar]] described Ewen's 1980 article, “City Lights: Immigrant Women and the Rise of the Movies,” in ''Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society'', as 'the first significant writing by a historian on early American cinema to follow the author's and [Garth] Jowett's books.”<ref>Robert Sklar, "Oh! Althusser!: Historiography and the Rise of Cinema Studies ," Radical History Review 41 (1988): 27,</ref> Ewen's book, ''Immigrant Women in the Land of Dollars'', examined the role of cinema in the lives of immigrant girls and women in New York City's [[Lower East Side]].<ref name="Roberson1998">{{cite book|author=Susan L. Roberson|title=Women, America, and Movement: Narratives of Relocation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gqdrTcP45qkC&pg=PA119|year=1998|publisher=University of Missouri Press|isbn=978-0-8262-1176-7|pages=119–}}</ref> [[Filmmaker]] Ellen Noonan has explained that the book was the inspiration for the 1993 documentary ''Heaven Will Protect the Working Girl''.<ref>http://nowandthen.ashp.cuny.edu/2012/06/remembering-elizabeth-ewen/</ref>

Elizabeth Ewen authored several books with her husband, [[media historian]] [[Stuart Ewen]],<ref name="Danna1992">{{cite book|author=Sammy Richard Danna|title=Advertising and Popular Culture: Studies in Variety and Versatility|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UjO5ohzPBcQC&pg=PA23|year=1992|publisher=Popular Press|isbn=978-0-87972-528-0|pages=23–}}</ref> and her colleague [[Rosalyn Baxandall]],<ref name="AgnewRosenzweig2008">{{cite book|author1=Jean-Christophe Agnew|author2=Roy Rosenzweig|title=A Companion to Post-1945 America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tcbk_ERH6MgC&pg=PA250|date=15 April 2008|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4051-2319-8|pages=250–}}</ref><ref>[http://www.readcube.com/articles/10.1111%2F1467-9906.00124?r3_referer=wol&tracking_action=preview_click&show_checkout=1 "Picture Windows: Suburbs Happen"].''Journal of Urban Affairs'' Volume 24, Issue 2</ref> including ''Channels of Desire: Mass Images and the Shaping of American Consciousness'' (1992),<ref name="Ross1999">{{cite book|author=Steven J. Ross|title=Working-class Hollywood: Silent Film and the Shaping of Class in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7k1rb0XT6TEC&pg=PA287|year=1999|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0-691-02464-2|pages=287–}}</ref> ''Picture Windows: How the Suburbs Happened'' (2000), ''Typecasting: On the Arts and Sciences of Human Inequality'' (2006).<ref>http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=157878129</ref>

Ewen's work is frequently cited by contemporary [[historian|historians]].<ref name="Prieto2001">{{cite book|author=Laura R. Prieto|title=At Home in the Studio: The Professionalization of Women Artists in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0bcXHa08knsC&pg=PA256|year=2001|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-00486-3|pages=256–}}</ref><ref name="HistoryHistory1990">{{cite book|author1=Institute of Contemporary Jewry The Hebrew University of Jerusalem Ezra Mendelsohn Professor of History|author2=Institute of Contemporary Jewry The Hebrew University of Jerusalem Richard I. Cohen Professor of History|title=Studies in Contemporary Jewry : Volume VI: Art and Its Uses|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sAYQzFm1ZfsC&pg=PA362|date=30 November 1990|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-506188-8|pages=362–}}</ref>

Elizabeth Ewen died May 29, 2012 in [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/nytimes/obituary.aspx?pid=157878129 "ELIZABETH R. EWEN - Obituary".</ref>

==Selected publications==
